9. Why This Works

For every substring

sum(l,r)

=

prefix[r+1]

-

prefix[l]

We need

sum > 0

which means

prefix[r+1]

>

prefix[l]

So every previous prefix smaller than the current prefix forms one valid substring ending at the current position.

Fenwick Tree efficiently counts these previous smaller prefix sums.


