> "I first convert every 1 into +1 and every 0 into -1. Then the problem becomes counting subarrays with positive sum. Using prefix sums, a substring is valid if prefix[r+1] > prefix[l]. Therefore, for each prefix sum, I count how many previous prefix sums are smaller. Since prefix sums can be negative, I perform coordinate compression and use a Fenwick Tree to maintain frequencies of prefix sums. Each query and update takes O(log n), giving an overall complexity of O(n log n)."




---

12. Key Takeaways

Convert binary values into +1 and -1.

The problem becomes counting positive-sum subarrays.

Prefix sums convert subarray sums into prefix differences.

Condition becomes prefix[j] > prefix[i].

Fenwick Tree efficiently counts previous smaller prefix sums.

Coordinate compression handles negative prefix values.

Overall complexity: O(n log n).



---

13. Common Mistakes

Using >= instead of > when comparing prefix sums.

Forgetting to include the initial prefix sum 0.

Not coordinate-compressing negative prefix sums.

Querying the BIT after updating it, which incorrectly counts the current prefix.

Using raw prefix sums as Fenwick Tree indices.



